<% content_for :title, "Managing Customers — Admin Manual" %>

<div class="flex gap-8 lg:gap-12">
  <aside class="hidden lg:block w-52 flex-shrink-0">
    <%= render "sidebar" %>
  </aside>

  <article class="min-w-0 flex-1">
    <%= render BreadcrumbComponent.new(items: [
      { label: "Admin Manual", path: admin_docs_path },
      { label: "Customers", path: nil }
    ]) %>

    <h1 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900">Managing Customers</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-stone-500">Search, view, create, and edit customer accounts.</p>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-8 text-stone-700">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">How Customers Sign Up</h2>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
          <p>
            Customers can now register themselves using the <strong>Sign Up</strong> link in the
            public navigation. They enter an email address and password, then verify their email
            before they can hold or pay for studio time.
          </p>
          <p>
            Self-registered customers appear in the Customers list as soon as they complete
            registration. They cannot book until their email is verified — you'll see their bookings
            blocked by the verification gate in the meantime.
          </p>
          <p>
            You can still create accounts manually (see below) for customers who contact you by
            phone or email. Admin-created accounts are automatically email-verified so those
            customers can book immediately.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">Searching Customers</h2>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
          <p>
            Go to <strong>Customers</strong> and type a name or email address into the search bar.
            Partial matches work — you don't need to type the full name. Results update as you type.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">Viewing a Customer Profile</h2>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
          <p>Click any customer to see their profile, which includes:</p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 list-disc pl-5">
            <li>Profile photo (if the customer has uploaded one), name, email address, and phone number</li>
            <li><strong>Total spend</strong> — amount paid across all confirmed and completed bookings</li>
            <li><strong>Booking history</strong> — a table of every booking with dates, duration, cost, and status</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Customers who haven't uploaded a photo show a letter avatar based on their name or
            email address. Profile photos are face-cropped automatically.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">Creating a Customer Account</h2>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
          <p>
            Go to <strong>Customers → New Customer</strong>. Enter their email address, name, and phone number.
          </p>
          <p>
            The app generates a temporary password automatically and marks the account as
            email-verified, so the customer can book immediately. They should use
            <strong>Forgot Password</strong> on the sign-in page to set their own password the first
            time they sign in. You don't need to share the generated password with them.
          </p>
          <p>
            Use this workflow when a customer calls or emails to book — create their account first,
            then create the booking under their name.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">Editing Customer Info</h2>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
          <p>
            From any customer profile, click <strong>Edit</strong>. You can update their name and
            phone number. Email addresses cannot be changed after account creation.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</div>
